= If an act of worship is mixed with riyā’ (showing off)

*There are three cases:*


*First case:*

The initial motive for the act was to show off to people.

 Ruling: This is shirk (associating partners with Allāh), and the act of worship is invalid.


*Second case:*

The act was initially for Allāh, but riyā’ appeared later during the act.

This has two possible situations:

 1. The person fights it and does not give in to the riyā’: This does not affect his worship.
 2. The person becomes content with the riyā’ and continues with it without resisting: The ruling here depends on the nature of the worship.

*A) * If the latter part of the act is not built on the first part. Then the first part is valid, and the part affected by riyā’ is invalid.
 
 Example: 

 A man gives ₹100 sincerely for Allāh, then sees someone and gives another ₹100 to show off. The first donation is valid, the second is invalid.

*B)* If the latter part depends on the first part (as in continuous acts like prayer). Then the entire act is invalid.

 Example: 
 
 A man begins a two-unit prayer sincerely for Allāh, then in the second unit starts showing off and doesn’t resist it. The entire prayer becomes invalid.

*Third case:*

 When riyā’ occurs after completing the act of worship.

Ruling: This does not affect the validity or reward of the act.

*Note:*

If someone hears praise from others and feels happy about it, there is nothing wrong with that.
In fact, the Prophet #pbuh was asked about a man who does a good deed, and the people praise him for it. He said: #hadith-block[تِلْكَ عَاجِلُ بُشْرَى الْمُؤْمِنِ][“That is the early glad tidings for the believer.”
(Narrated by Muslim)@muslim[vol. 6, pp. 498--99, \#2731]]



*Issue: What about a person who leaves an act out of fear of people?*

Leaving a good deed for the sake of people is also a form of riyā’.


*Difference between riyā’ and Sam’ah (seeking to be heard):*

 Riyā’ relates to what is seen, like doing an act so people will see and praise the person.

 Sam’ah relates to what is heard. Meaning doing or speaking about an act so people will hear and praise a person.


*Treatment for riyā’:*

 1. Remembering the virtues of sincerity (ikhlās).
 
 2. Reflecting on the danger of riyā’, that it nullifies deeds.
 
 3. Remembering the Hereafter and that only Allāh can reward.
 
 4. Knowing that people have no power to benefit or harm you.
 
 5. Making du’ā (supplication) such as: #hadith-block[ اللهُمَّ إِنَّا نَعُوذُ بِكَ مِنْ أَنْ نُشْرِكَ بِكَ شَيْئًا نَعْلَمُهُ، وَنَسْتَغْفِرُكَ لِمَا لَا نَعْلَمُ][] “O Allāh, we seek refuge in You from associating anything with You knowingly, and we seek Your forgiveness for what we do unknowingly.” (Narratedby Aḥmad and graded as good (Ḥasan) by Al-Albāni – #mercyBOTH @ahmad[vol. 32, pp. 383--84, \#19606])


 == Table (If an Act of Worship Is Mixed With Showing Off (Riyā’) )

1. If the original intention from the start is to impress people

   This is shirk, and the act of worship is invalid.

2. If he intended it for Allah, then showing off entered later
A. If he fights it and does not give in to it

→ In this case, it does not affect him.

B. If he accepts it and goes along with it, without resisting it
• If the act of worship is of the type that one part depends on another (connected act)

→ The whole act of worship becomes invalid.

• If the act of worship is of the type where one part does not depend on another (separate/repeatable act)

→ The first part is valid, and whatever riyā’ entered into later is invalid.

3. If riyā’ occurs after completing the act of worship

→ It does not affect the act of worship at all.

 
 

